article.headline: Florida State 69, Clemson 59
article.story: TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Al Thornton felt no pain from a knee bruise that hobbled him three days earlier but he put some hurt on Clemson while leading Florida State to a 69-59 victory Wednesday night with 15 points. Florida State broke open a close game with a 14-0 run in the second half and then held off the Tigers, who had defeated the Seminoles 61-55 last month at Clemson, S.C. Thornton, Florida State's season scoring leader with a 17.7 average going into the game, bruised his left knee Sunday when Miami held him scoreless as the Hurricanes won in overtime. "My knee felt great," Thornton said. "I did a lot of warming up. Once it got loose, it felt great." He had a brace on the knee but took it off before the tipoff. "I never played with a brace on, and it was very irritating," Thornton said. "I couldn't move with it on." Jason Rich added 13 points and Alexander Johnson had 12 as the Seminoles surpassed the 12 games they won all last season by increasing their overall record to 13-5. They evened their Atlantic Coast Conference mark at 4-4. Julius Powell led Clemson (14-7, 3-5) with 14 points while Akin Akingbala had 13 and Vernon Hamilton scored 11. "Like most ACC games, this was what you might call a `battle royale,' " said Florida State coach Leonard Hamilton. "This was a typical rock 'em, sock 'em, bang 'em aggressive ACC game." Referees called 43 personal fouls -- 26 on Clemson and 17 on Florida State -- and Hamilton drew a technical. The Tigers hit 13 of 18 free throws and the Seminoles 29 of 35. Both teams had 20 turnovers. Florida State's multiple defense caused problems for the Tigers all night, said Clemson coach Oliver Purnell. First it was a zone, then man-to-man and finally a full-court press. "We did a poor job adjusting to their physicalness," Purnell said. "Against full-court pressure we weren't executing at all. We were throwing the ball back toward the basket and that's exactly opposite of what we want to do." The Seminoles outscored the Tigers 40 to 28 in the paint and both teams were cold from outside the three-point line. Florida State missed all nine of its three-point attempts while Clemson hit four of 21. Thornton gave Florida State a 5-4 lead with a three-point play and the Seminoles never trailed again although Clemson tied the score once during a ragged first half and twice in the second half. The Seminoles broke the final 49-49 tie by scoring 14 unanswered points. Clemson was unable to get closer than 10 the rest of the way.
